<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Actress Winnie Ntshaba, the founder of the awards, told Daily Sun she was excited that the awards were back and happy that the department of arts and culture was helping to fund them.“We had a challenge with funding and had to withdraw, but now things are back in full swing.“We need more of these awards as actors. Just look at the music industry and the multiple award ceremonies they host.” Winnie said the industry was a tough place and that people needed to appreciate the outstanding work that actors, actresses and people working behind the scenes do. The list of nominees honoured some of the usual suspects and some unexpected surprises. Mzansi Magic’s Isibaya and Isithembiso led with 18 nominations combined, followed by SABC 3’s Isidingo and SABC 1’s Skeem Saam, with 11 nominations.In the category of most Popular Soapie of the Year, 7de Laan, Generations: The Legacy and Uzalo will go head to head.The public will have the opportunity to vote for their favourite performers in the lead role and in supporting character categories, as well as for the most popular soapie of the year. Voting platforms will open on 8 May and close on 8 June. The voting codes are available on the website www.royaltysa.com.